#: Game.Levels.NaturalNumbersWorld
msgid "In this world, we will introduce the type В§0 of natural numbers.\n"
"\n"
"In traditional foundations, the natural numbers are characterized by a series of axioms discovered roughly contemporaneously by Dedekind and Peano that are commonly called the *Peano postulates*. There are five axioms:\n"
"\n"
"  1. There is a natural number В§1 called *zero*.\n"
"\n"
"  2. There is a function В§2 that sends any natural number to its *successor*.\n"
"\n"
"  3. The successor function is injective: В§3.\n"
"\n"
"  4. Zero is not the successor of any natural number: В§4.\n"
"\n"
"  5. The principle of mathematical induction: В§5.\n"
"\n"
"In type theory, the type В§6 of natural numbers is instead characterized by introduction and elimination rules:\n"
"\n"
"* The *introduction rules* tell us that there is a natural number В§7 as well as natural numbers obtained by applying the function В§8.\n"
"* The *elimination rule* extends the principle of mathematical induction to families of types as well as families of propositions: В§9.\n"
"\n"
"Together these rules say that В§10 is an *inductive type* freely generated by В§11 and В§12. We may define (dependent) functions out of the inductive type В§13 &ldquo;by induction&rdquo; by considering only the cases of В§14 and В§15 for some В§16.\n"
"\n"
"The type-theoretic definition of В§17 closely resembles Peano's first, second, and fifth axioms and in fact implies the other two, as we will see by the end of this world."
msgstr ""

