#: Game.Levels.EquivalenceWorld
msgid "What does it mean for two things to be &ldquo;the same&rdquo;?\n"
"\n"
"The answer depends on what sort of things we are talking about.\n"
"\n"
"We have seen what it means for two elements of the same type to be the same. Given В§0, we think of В§1 and В§2 as being &ldquo;the same&rdquo; if they are *equal*, meaning there is an element В§3 in the equality type.\n"
"\n"
"We have also seen what it means for two propositions to be the same. Given propositions В§4 and В§5, we think of В§6 and В§7 as being &ldquo;the same&rdquo; if they are *logically equivalent*, meaning there is an element В§8.\n"
"\n"
"What does it mean for two types to be &ldquo;the same&rdquo;?\n"
"\n"
"In this level, we will learn the answer: two types В§9 and В§10 are &ldquo;the same&rdquo; if they are *equivalent*. This means there is some element В§11 in the type В§12 of *equivalences* between В§13 and В§14 that we will introduce.\n"
"\n"
"To define an equivalence between В§15 and В§16 we need four pieces of data:\n"
"\n"
"* a function В§17\n"
"* a function В§18\n"
"* a proof В§19\n"
"* a proof В§20\n"
"\n"
"The first two pieces of data resemble the data required by a logical equivalence В§21. For that one needs proofs В§22 and В§23 of the implications in each direction.\n"
"\n"
"The remaining data is relevant because functions carry more information than implications. In particular, there may be multiple functions from В§24 to В§25 and from В§26 to В§27.\n"
"\n"
"By function extensionality, the proof В§28 witnesses the fact that В§29 while the proof В§30 witnesses the fact that В§31. Together this tells us that the functions В§32 and В§33 are *inverses*.\n"
"\n"
"In other words, if В§34 and В§35 are thought of as operations that exchange elements of types В§36 and В§37, both operations can be undone by applying the other operation.\n"
"\n"
"The data В§38 is sometimes also referred to as an *isomorphism* or a *bijection* but in Lean the term *equivalence* is more common."
msgstr ""

