#: Game.Levels.DisjunctionWorld
msgid "The logical connective of *disjunction*, denoted by В§0, is the mathematical version of *or*.\n"
"\n"
"For arbitrary propositions В§1 and В§2, В§3 is a new proposition asserting that at least one of В§4 *or* В§5 *are true*.\n"
"\n"
"To understand how conjunctions work in logic we must learn:\n"
"\n"
"* How to prove theorems of the form В§6.\n"
"* How to use a hypothesis of the form В§7 to prove something else.\n"
"\n"
"There are two strategies to prove В§8. It suffices to supply a proof of В§9 and it also suffices to supply a proof of В§10.\n"
"\n"
"Note that the mathematical &ldquo;or&rdquo; is *inclusive*, meaning that if В§11 and В§12 are both true, then В§13 is true.\n"
"\n"
"Together these strategies define the two introduction rules for disjunctions. Note that a proof that employs either of these strategies carries extra information. In addition to concluding that В§14 is true, a proof using the first strategy will prove along the way that В§15 is true (perhaps subject to certain hypotheses) while a proof using the second strategy will prove along the way that В§16 is true (perhaps subject to other hypotheses).\n"
"\n"
"Similarly, the construction of an element of a coproduct type via either of the introduction rules will carry the information of whether the element comes from the left-hand type or the right-hand type.\n"
"\n"
"The elimination rule for disjunctions explains how to use a hypothesis В§17 to prove something else.\n"
"\n"
"Using a hypothesis В§18 leads to a proof strategy of arguing &ldquo;by cases&rdquo; as we will soon discover.\n"
"\n"
"Like the analogy between function types and implication, and product types and conjunction, there is a close analogy between coproduct types and the logical operation of disjunction.\n"
"\n"
"In particular, we will use similar notations and the same tactics introduced in Coproduct World."
msgstr ""

